r 1418","1349":"1349","ABT 1371":"circa 1371","1347":"1347","about 1349":"circa 1349","1323":"1323","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","about 1345":"circa 1345","about 1378":"circa 1378","before 18 August 1419":"vóór 18 augustus 1419","1419":"1419","1319":"1319","1418":"1418","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Blakiston Hall, Durham, England":"Durham, England","Blakiston, Durham, England":"Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1345–before 18 August 1419":"about 1345–before 18 August 1419","1345–1419":"1345–1419","1362–Male":"1362–Deceased","1347–Female":"1347–Deceased","1378–1418":"1378–1418","1319–1349":"1319–1349","1323–Female":"1323–Deceased","ABT 1345":"about 1345","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","before 1418":"before 1418","1349":"1349","ABT 1371":"about 1371","1347":"1347","about 1349":"about 1349","1323":"1323","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","about 1345":"about 1345","about 1378":"about 1378","before 18 August 1419":"before 18 August 1419","1419":"1419","1319":"1319","1418":"1418","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Blakiston Hall, Durham, England":"Durham, England","Blakiston, Durham, England":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Blakiston","type":"LAST","meanings":["Blaec, black, isc, signifying likeness, and tun, town, meaning a blackish town"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Blakiston was born about 1345, in Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de  Blakinston, was 28 an